[1] Liberia (Peace Island, Montserrado county)
Date: Wed 25 Mar 2015
Source: Heritage Newspaper [edited]
http://www.heritageliberia.net/heritagenews/index.php/2014-07-17-10-02-56/other-headlines/444-measles-outbreak-hits-peace-island-community


Medecins San Frontieres (MSF)-France has vaccinated over 400 children against measles in the Peace Island Community, outside Monrovia. Peace Island is a slum and congested community located in district no. 10, Montserrado County. The initiative by the health charity group came in the wake of confirmed reports of the outbreak of measles in that area.

In an interview with this paper at the weekend [21-22 Mar 2015], a Physician Assistant in charge of the vaccination center, Mr Allen Cooper, disclosed that a 2-day vaccination campaign was launched in the community following an assessment carried out by both MSF-France and the Ministry of Health and Social Welfare. He stated that few cases of measles were identified and therefore MSF-France intervened to help save the children in the community. He said children from 6 months old to 5 years benefited from free immunization against measles.

"We came here along with the Ministry of Health and Social Welfare recently and we identified few cases of measles after testing the specimens of the patients. During the screening process at the vaccine center, we basically noticed that 2 children had measles, and so, we immediately isolated them at the isolation unit," he stated.

At the same time, a nurse assigned at the center, Ihuoma Bondo, has urged parents, whose children have taken the vaccines, to seek medical attention at a hospital or clinic if their child/children experience negative reactions within the period of 2 weeks.

She said vaccines as usual may cause hotness in one's body temperature, and therefore, she suggested that parents or guardians should bathe their children showing this kind of sign with cold water. She encouraged parents or guardians to observe their children for "rashes or itching from now to [2 Apr 2015]," and also avoid "pressing the vaccine's hand with hot water."

"Vaccine can make the children skin hot and so, if you go home and observe it don't worry; just bathe the child with cold water and give the child paracetamol. Some people can react to vaccine or medicine too if the medicine does not agree with them; like for example, small itches or rashes will come on their skin.

"Don't rub vase on the place the vaccine was given to your children," Madam Bondo urged.

[Byline: Obediah Johnson]

