[7] USA (Payne County, Oklahoma)
Date: Fri 27 Mar 2015
Source: KJRH-TV [summ., edited]
http://www.kjrh.com/news/health/oklahoma-state-department-of-health-announces-confirmed-case-of-measles-virus-in-stillwater


According to the Oklahoma State Department of Health [OSDH], a patient in Stillwater [Payne County] was recently diagnosed with the virus -- the 1st confirmed case in Oklahoma since 1997. The patient, who has traveled internationally, is the spouse of an Oklahoma State University student who lives off campus.

OSDH is working with the Payne County Health Department, OSU and local medical facilities to investigate possible exposure risks. According to OSDH, persons who visited the following Stillwater locations may have been exposed to the virus:

- Aldi (1188 N Perkins Rd) [13 Mar 2015]
- Crepe Myrtle Market (613 S Lewis) [13 Mar 2015]
- Food Pyramid (421 N Maine St) [13 Mar 2015]
- Boba Fusion Cafe (211 N Perkins Rd) [13 Mar 2015]
- China Wok (917 N Perkins Rd) [14 Mar 2015]
- Jimmy's Egg (811 W 6th Ave) [16 Mar 2015]
- University Health Services [17 or 19 Mar 2015]
- Will Rogers Airport [12 Mar 2015, from 9:30 pm - 1:30 am. A spokesperson for the City of Oklahoma City says the patient was a passenger on a United Airlines Flight from Houston's George Bush Intercontinental Airport [Thu 12 Mar 2015]. The flight arrive at the Will Rogers World Airport at 9:30 pm.

Measles is a highly contagious respiratory disease, which can be spread up to 4 days before the onset of a rash until 4 days after the rash begins. The measles vaccine (MMR vaccine) is recommended for all children 12 to 15 months of age and again between 4 to 6 years of age. Boosters may be given at any age thereafter. 2 vaccine doses normally provide lifelong immunity.

Measles can cause pneumonia and other complications, especially in young children and adults older than 20. Pregnant women and those with weakened immune systems can experience serious problems from measles.

