[8] CDC weekly update
Date: Mon 23 Mar 2015
Source: CDC, Measles Home, Measles cases and outbreaks, weekly update [summ., edited]
http://www.cdc.gov/measles/cases-outbreaks.html


From 1 Jan to 20 Mar 2015, 178 people from 17 states and the District of Columbia were reported to have measles [Arizona (7), California (120), Colorado (1), District of Columbia(2), Delaware (1), Georgia (1), Illinois (15), Michigan (1), Minnesota (1), Nebraska (2), New Jersey (2), New York (3), Nevada (9), Pennsylvania (1), South Dakota (2) Texas (1), Utah (2), Washington (7)]. Most of these cases [131 cases (74 percent)] are part of a large, ongoing multi-state outbreak linked to an amusement park in California.

The United States experienced a record number of measles cases during 2014, with 644 cases from 27 states reported to CDC's National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases (NCIRD). This is the greatest number of cases since measles elimination was documented in the US in 2000.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Since Disney-related cases were first confirmed in December 2014, that outbreak has involved 146 cases, 130 of which involved people in California. The Montreal area has had at least 188 Disney-linked measles cases, according to local reports.

In addition to the Disney-linked outbreak, the United States has had unrelated outbreaks in Illinois, Nevada, and Washington state. The 4 outbreaks represent 89 percent of total cases this year (2015), according to the CDC. - Mod.CP

According to the reports above, the total as of 27 Mar 2015, is 183 cases from 19 states (new cases have been reported from California, Oklahoma, and Florida since the CDC update of 20 Mar 2015). A map showing the states where cases of measles have been reported as of 23 Mar 2015 (it does not include the case reported from Florida or Oklahoma) can be seen at http://www.orlandoweekly.com/imager/measles-case-confirmed-in-traveler-who-vis/b/original/2376288/902d/cdc.jpg. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

